{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu) chapter 6, which details the duties of the hermit (va-naprastha, or forest-dweller), the precise rule states that he \"should always wear matted hair, and his beard, body hair, and nails.\"**[^1]\n\nThis is prescribed in verse 6.6, as part of the external observances for one entering the third āśrama after the householder stage: \"He should wear a skin or a garment of bark; he should bathe in the evening and in the morning; and he should always wear matted hair, and his beard, body hair, and nails.\"[^1] The phrasing indicates that these are to be left untrimmed—matted locks (jaṭā), a full beard (śmaśru), body hair (loma), and nails (nakhā)—in contrast to the final ascetic stage (saṃnyāsin), whose \"hair, nails, and beard [are to be] clipped\" (6.52).[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, ch. 6, [p-89d810](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/#p-89d810).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, ch. 6, [p-ed3d57](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/#p-ed3d57).",
